The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, December 15, 2003 				 Manufacturing gathers momentum: CII report
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, Dec. 14: The Indian economy is on a bullish trend with the manufacturing sector gaining momentum and overall demand picking up, says the CII-Ascon survey for the period April-September this year. The survey says production trends confirm a continuity of growth in the manufacturing sector seen in last fiscal and in the first quarter of the current financial year. 																								The survey adds that though there has been a decline in the number of sectors of excellent growth compared with the previous corresponding period, there has been an increase in the number of sectors achieving high growth.																								Sectors covered include machine tools, commercial vehicles, light commercial vehicles, utility vehicles, cars, three wheelers, aluminium, fluid power components which have showed excellent growth. Others sectors, like electronic components, paints, sponge iron, soda ash are in the high growth sectors.																								The survey also reveals that hydrogen gas, processed fruit and vegetables have achieved moderate growth from negative growth during the same period last year. Mopeds, vanaspati, black-and-white televisions, edible oil, groundnut oil, cigarettes and tobacco are on the negative list.																								However, some sectors, which have moved from negative to positive growth compared with the corresponding period last year are cars, scooters, utility vehicles, diesel engines, textile machinery and hydro-electric power.																								The survey states that six sectors have achieved excellent sales growth, 22 sectors have registered high growth, while 48 sectors have indicated low or negative sales growth. Fluid power components, machine tools, cars, light commercial vehicles, utility vehicles fall in the excellent sales growth category, and others, including aluminium, paints, soda ash, auto components, diesel engines, rubber goods, are in the high sales growth sector.																								Sectors, which achieved negative sales growth are caustic soda, crude oil, oil and gas equipment, textile machinery, electrical cables and wires.																								The survey also points out that overall picture of exports as compared with the previous corresponding quarter is rosy. The survey reveals that exports are higher in many sectors and have improved position over the last three quarters. 
